<http://www.isid.org>
[1] _Citrus tristeza virus_, huanglongbing - Philippines (Kalinga)
[2] Unspecified diseases - India (Mizoram)
******
[1] _Citrus tristeza virus_, huanglongbing - Philippines (Kalinga)
Date: 21 Jan 2008
Source: Philippine Information Agency [edited]
<http://www.pia.gov.ph/?m=12&r=&y=&mo=&fi=p080121.htm&no=15>

There is a new hope for citrus growers of the famous Kalinga Oranges
commonly known as "gayunan" in this town after the National Economic
Development Authority (NEDA) and the local government unit (LGU) allotted
through a Memorandum of Agreement P 990 000 [24 535 USD] to revive the
industry.
The project intends to produce and distribute good quality, disease-free
gayunan seedlings through the procurement of certified disease-free
imported citrus seeds and asexual propagation or side-grafting which
hastens the propagation and distribution of budded seedlings. Major
activities would include construction of plastic and screen houses,
seedling propagation, establishment of foundation groves for budwoods and
rootstocks, and training on Citrus Production and Management for
farmer-producers to ensure the sustainability of the program.
Famous for its tastier, more juicy, and sweeter taste, the gayunan was a
major source of income of the people in the early 1960s, but the industry
started to decline in the early 1980s due to the damage brought by the
systemic diseases leaf mottling [citrus greening, huanglongbing] and the
_Citrus tristeza virus_, aside from poor orchard management and minimal
expansion of gayunan orchards because of the lack of planting materials.
The local government decided to devise methods and experiments to address
the crisis. Signed on 7 Dec 2007, the project is expected to be
accomplished within the year.
--
